etymologies: mid 16th century; earliest use found in Andrew of Wyntoun (c1350–c1422), prior of St Serf's, Lochleven, and historian. Either (i) from classical Latin titulāre to title

definitions: To give a specified name or title to (something); to designate, style, call. Also: to speak of or describe (something) as being of a particular kind or possessing a particular quality.

notes.text: Not in common use after the 18th century; now only in occasional use in humorous, informal contexts.
